review_blob:
Frothy head, nice retention. Cloudy gold orange body. Sweet, peppery citrus tang on the nose. Sharp and dry in the mouth. Taste matches the aroma. 
Overall, I'm very happy with this beer and will buy another bottle tomorrow.

beer_name: Granville Island One-Two Punch Belgian IPA

review_blob:
Pours a clear auburn, with ample tan head. Very good retention and nice lacing. Still a finger of foam, down half a glass. Aroma of caramel, nuts, light pine. Creamy mouthfeel, moderate carbonation. The flavor profile is more toward the malts, sweet caramel, slightly syrupy with just a light dose of citrus hops. Overall a smooth pale ale that leans toward an English style bitter.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Powell Street Old Jalopy Pale Ale

review_blob:
Dark brown, opaque. Thin tan head. Aroma of ripe fruit and molasses. Flavor profile is malt based and lightly smokey with notes of raisins and prunes. Mouthfeel is thick and rich with a sharp carbonated finish. This Trappiste Ale goes perfect with a deep, plush sofa. Savor, and enjoy the warm buzz.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pours a clear amber with tan head. Faint aroma of citrus hops on top of caramel malts. Taste is a bit thin. Light malt sweetness and mild hop bitterness. I have had better red ales and was hoping for more out of this one. ---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pours a slightly hazy gold-orange. Moderate white head. The nose is lightly citrus with faint notes of caramel. Mouthfeel Leans toward sharp and dry. The taste blends nicely from the citrus hops to the smooth pale malt base. Overall, I gotta say this an impressive session ale which I would recommend for all occasions. It's smooth and easy at 4.4%, and my taste buds are totally satisfied.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Subtle aroma of roasted malts and tilled earth. Dark auburn body with ample frothy tan head. (Think rootbeer float) Mouthfeel is slightly sharp. Medium-high carbonation shows in a steady stream of bubbles from the base of the glass. Taste is mellow and roasty, with a limited hop presence. Overall, a decent representation of the "old" German ale. I'd take another if offered, but, afraid to say my taste buds are eyeing up the imperial IPA in the fridge.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pours a golden body with ample white head from the wheat. Aroma of pears and pineapple. The taste is grapefruit with a side of toasted buttered biscuits. Mouthfeel is medium carbonation, creamy and sticky. The beer reminds me of La gunitas- a little sumpin' sumpin' but a little more rough around the edges. Overall a great beer. Refreshing, flavourful and a nice twist the IPA style.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Pick a hop pack. 341ml, 6%abv. As the name says, it pours ruby, if not amber in color. The head is tight, and tan colored. It has good retention, and sticks to the glass. Subtle aroma with notes of molasses, and sweet citrus. The smooth base of pale, crystal, and victory malt is well complimented by the cascade hops. Medium carbonation    
and some chewiness. Overall, smooth, satisfying, and a good example of a hop forward amber ale.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Poured from a 650ml bomber. 7.2% abv. Cloudy, burnt orange in color. Generous fluffy white head. Nice lacing on the glass. The northwest hops give off a floral aroma with sweet melon and citrus     
notes. Despite being loaded with 4 types of hops the flavor profile is relatively mellow, with creamy grapefruit  , pale malts, and a smooth finish. Nice.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Parallel 49 Lord of the Hops IPA

review_blob:
Purchased in a 4 pack of bottles. It pours black as night. The head demands attention with 3 fingers of chocolate milk foam. There is good retention, maintaining a nice layer on the stout, and sticking all the way down the glass. There is a delicious aroma of roasted malts. Taste is more of the same roasted malts with notes of coffee and bitter dark chocolate. Mouthfeel is smooth with moderate carbonation. Goes down easy even at 9%abv. Alcohol warming is present, and I'm feeling comfortably numb. Overall, a very smooth, satisfying, and highly drinkable imperial stout.

        

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

beer_name: Lagunitas A Little Sumpin Sumpin Ale

review_blob:
Purchased a 650ml bomber for St. Patty's Day. Poured a dark, clear, auburn body, with fluffy french vanilla head. The head leaves nice trails on the glass as it dissipates, and settles with a nice milky lace. The aroma suggests caramel malts and Ceylon tea. More caramel and tea on the tongue with an appearance of PNW hops to balance things out nicely. Mouthfeel is smooth, medium bodied, light-medium carbonation. Overall, pleasantly surprised, and I would reach for this one again.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Appearance- golden orange, clear body. Ample tan coloured head leaves nice lacing on the glass and a creamy film on top.
Aroma- crack the can and you're hit in the face with a fistful o' hops. After pouring it opens up nicely. Floral, citric and pungent.
Mouthfeel- medium body and carbonation. Nice feel and chewiness from the hop oils.
Taste- grapefruits, pale malts, and a lingering bitter finish. 
Overall- top class IPA that I'd put up against any in the PNW.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Poured from a 500ml can. Dark amber body. Off white head. Nice lacing. Aroma is light maltiness. Mouthfeel is thin, but grainy. Medium-high carbonation. Taste is sweet, biscuity, light caramel malts, mild bitterness. A simple, easy drinking amber ale.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Poured from a 500ml can. Orange amber clear body. Off white colored head which leaves nice lacing on the glass. Aroma is biscuity with faint citrus notes. Mouthfeel is grainy with medium-high carbonation. Taste is once again, biscuity, and there's a light bitter finish from the hops. Overall taste is a bit thin compared other PNW Pale Ales, but will gladly choose over a macro.

beer_brewer_name: American Brewing Company (Pacific Brewing & Malting Company)
review_blob:
High carbonation, and soft pillow of white foam on top. Recedes a bit then floats on top of a gold orange body. Slightly spicy almost Belgian aroma. Mouthfeel is dry, sharp carbonation, medium body. Taste is lightly bitter, spicy jalapeo Gouda cheese, toffee, and passion fruit. Seems quite a bit different than most NW IPAs. Drinkable even at 7.2%, but there are better IPAs in Washington and BC.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Body is appropriately a dark chocolate brown. Taste is okay. Hints of molasses. May appeal to some due the chocolate, but I find it comes off flat. Overall I'm disappointed, this was much better a few years ago.
